nodes.title: LCM
widgets_values: Set to use LCM by default for the txt2img generation.

nodes.title: Frame Rates
widgets_values: Don't be afraid to play with your frame rates depending on the type of animation you are creating.

nodes.title: Suggestions
widgets_values: Play with motion_bucket_id and augmentation_level to fine tune your animations.

nodes.title: Hint
widgets_values: Motion Bucket and Video Seed will make the biggest differences in your output.  Don't be afraid to experiment.  If you don't like the preview animation, change one of those and Queue again for a new result.  Motion Bucket has a high range. I've used settings as high as 250 on the right animation.

nodes.title: Landscape/Portrait swap
widgets_values: The Frame size field here can be right clicked and select "swap width/height" to quickly switch between landscape and portrait.

nodes.title: Process Selection
widgets_values: Connect the appropriate input method here to the INPUT node to select your process.

nodes.title: Output Format Changes
widgets_values: You can change output formats and hit Queue again to save your video in a new format without having to render it all over again.

nodes.title: Ignore this error
widgets_values: This is just a useful tool that will list custom tags that trigger a specific LoRA.  The LoRA won't affect your render, it's just here to provide information. Not all LoRA have keywords, but this can help you remember them.

nodes.title: Ignore this error
widgets_values: Different process configurations can cause image input nodes to show a red error ring.  These can be ignored and are normal when we're not using all of the processes.

nodes.title: Connect for HiRes Fix
widgets_values:
Disconnect these two nodes until you are ready to generate your final output.

Connect these two nodes to generate your final output with a HiRes Fix version of the video after you've generated a preview you want to keep.  Once you connect, just hit "Queue Pompt" again and just the HiRes Fix will run and output your final animation.  This can take a bit.
photo of a humanoid werewolf, (wide brim black hat:1.2), (red long coat:1.2), howling at the moon.

nodes.title: Crash Note
widgets_values:
If you experience an out of memory crash the first time HirRes fix runs, just hit Queue again and it should fix itself.

I don't know why this happens to me so your mileage may vary. It's probably related to my only having 8gb of vram on my 3070.  Would gratefully accept a 4090 donation.

nodes.title: Video only seed
widgets_values: This seed is for video generation and is kept separate from the txt2img so that you can keep that image steady while experimenting with video effects.  If you don't like the preview, but like the image, change the video seed and run it again for a different effect.

nodes.title: Txt Prompt seed
widgets_values: This is the seed for txt2img generation.  It is recommended you keep this on fixed except when you want to generate a whole new image.  Doing so will allow you to play with your animation without having to generate a new image each time.

nodes.title: Release Notes
widgets_values:
v1.21 - Moved Connect for Final to the Configuration group.

v1.2 - Added a key for easier understanding of process connections. 
 - Added a useful LoRA query tool for those hard to remember LoRA keywords.  
  
v1.1 - Changed input selection to allow running of txt2img until happy with the result before moving to animation processing.

v1 - created 11/27/2023

Based on my core video experiment that didn't include HiRes Fix.  I've added toggles, and made it easier to experiment before committing to your final output.

I hope you find this useful.

--Clark Glenn Davis, aka Verevolf

nodes.title: Creation Process
widgets_values:
For your process you'll want to Render Stills Only until you have the starting image you want to use.  

Then set the Process Selector to do txt2vid and play with your video settings until you have the animation you want.

Finally, connect the Connect for Final nodes and render your finished video with HiRes Fix applied.

nodes.title: About Output Formats
widgets_values:
Your mileage may vary, but I've found .gif outputs best for showing on the web though they exhibit color banding due to their color palette limitations.

The best output format for me has been ProRes, the Apple .mov format.
